 all the engravings except the new frontispiece, appeared the next year (Hamburgh: B. G. Hoffmann, 1790).{{sfn|Carswell|1952a|p=173}}}} | Same contents as the Fifth Edition, plus a "Supplement" about a ride on an eagle and a new frontispiece. |- | Seventh | ''The Seventh Edition, Considerably enlarged, and ornamented with Twenty Explanatory Engravings, from Original Designs. Gulliver Revived: or, the Vice of Lying properly exposed. Containing singular Travels, Campaigns, Voyages, and Adventures in Russia, the Caspian Sea, Iceland, Turkey, Egypt, Gibraltar, up the Mediterranean, on the Atlantic Ocean and through the Centre of Mount Aetna, into the South Sea. Also, An Account of a Voyage into the Moon and Dog-Star; with many extraordinary Particulars relative to the Cooking Animal in those Planets, which are there called the Human Species. By Baron Munchausen'' | London: C. and G. Kearsley, 1793 | Same as the Sixth Edition. |- | Eighth | ''The Eighth Edition, Considerably enlarged, and ornamented with Twenty Explanatory Engravings, from Original Designs. Gulliver Revived: or, the Vice of Lying properly exposed. Containing singular Travels, Campaigns, Voyages, and Adventures in Russia, the Caspian Sea, Iceland, Turkey, Egypt, Gibraltar, up the Mediterranean, on the Atlantic Ocean and through the Centre of Mount Aetna, into the South Sea. Also, An Account of a Voyage into the Moon and Dog-Star; with many extraordinary Particulars relative to the Cooking Animal in those Planets, which are there called the Human Species. By Baron Munchausen'' | London: C. and G. Kearsley, 1799 | Same as the Sixth Edition. |} {| class="wikitable" width="100%" style="font-size:90%" ! colspan="4" | Early Munchausen translations and sequels |- ! Language ! Title ! Publication ! Contents |- | German | ''Wunderbare Reisen zu Wasser und Lande, feldzüge und lustige Abentheuer des Freyherrn von Münchhausen wie er dieselben bey der Flasche im Zirkel seiner Freunde zu Erzählen pflegt. Aus dem Englischen nach der neuesten Ausgabe übersetzt, hier und da erweitert und mit noch mehr Küpfern gezieret'' | London [actually Göttingen]: [Johann Christian Dieterich,] 1786 | Gottfried August Bürger's free translation of the English Second Edition, plus new material added by Bürger. Four illustrations from the English Second Edition and three new ones. |- | French | ''Gulliver ressuscité, ou les voyages, campagnes et aventures extraordinaires du Baron de Munikhouson'' | Paris: Royez, 1787 | Slightly modified translation of the English Fifth Edition. |- | German | ''Wunderbare Reisen zu Wasser und Lande, feldzüge und lustige Abentheuer des Freyherrn von Münchhausen, wie er dieselben bey der Flasche im Zirkel seiner Freunde zu Erzählen pflegt. Aus dem Englischen nach der neuesten Ausgabe übersetzt, hier und da erweitert und mit noch mehr Küpfern gezieret. Zweite vermehrte Ausgabe'' | London [actually Göttingen]: [Johann Christian Dieterich,] 1788 | Same as previous German edition, plus a translation of the new material from the English Fifth Edition, greatly revised. |- | German | ''Nachtrag zu den wunderbaren Reisen zu Wasser und Lande, und lustige Abentheuer des Freyherrn von Münchhausen, wie er dieselben bey der Flasch Wein im Zirkel seiner Freunde selbst zu erzählen pflegt. Mit Küpferrn'' | Copenhagen, 1789 | Original German sequel, sharply satirizing the Baron. Includes twenty-three engravings and an "Elegy on the Death of Herr von Münchhausen" (though the real-life Baron had not yet died). |- | English | ''A Sequel to the Adventures of Baron Munchausen humbly dedicated to Mr Bruce the Abyssinian Traveller, As the Baron conceives that it may be of some service to him making another expedition into Abyssinia; but if this does not delight Mr Bruce, the Baron is willing to fight him on any terms he pleases | [London:] H. D. Symonds, 1792 [a second edition was published 1796] | Original English sequel, satirizing the travels of [[James Bruce]]. Includes twenty engravings. This ''Sequel'' was often printed alongside the Raspe text as "Volume Two of the Baron's Travels". |}
==Fictional character== [[File:Münchhausen-AWille.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Refer to caption|Munchausen rides the cannonball, as pictured by [[August von Wille]].]] The fictional Baron Munchausen is a [[Alazon#Miles Gloriosus|braggart soldier]], most strongly defined by his comically exaggerated [[boast]]s about his own adventures;{{sfn|George|1918|pp=169–171}} all of the stories in Raspe's book are told in [[first-person narrative]], with a prefatory note explaining that "the Baron is supposed to relate these extraordinary Adventures over his Bottle, when surrounded by his Friends".{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=488}} The Baron's stories imply him to be a [[superhuman]] figure who spends most of his time either getting out of absurd predicaments or indulging in equally absurd moments of gentle mischief.{{sfn|Fisher|2006|p=253}} In some of his best-known stories, the Baron rides a [[Round shot|cannonball]], [[Moon in fiction|travels to the Moon]], is swallowed by a giant fish in the [[Mediterranean Sea]], saves himself from drowning by pulling on his own hair, fights a forty-foot crocodile, enlists a wolf to pull his sleigh, and uses [[Laurus nobilis|laurel tree]] branches to fix his horse when the animal is accidentally cut in two.{{sfn|Olry|2002|p=54}}
In the stories he narrates, the Baron is shown as a calm, [[rationality|rational]] man, describing what he experiences with simple [[objectivity (philosophy)|objectivity]]; absurd happenings elicit, at most, mild surprise from him, and he shows serious doubt about any unlikely events he has not witnessed himself.{{sfn|George|1918|pp=174–175}} The resulting narrative effect is an ironic tone, encouraging skepticism in the reader{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=484}} and marked by a running undercurrent of subtle [[satire|social satire]].{{sfn|Fisher|2006|p=253}} In addition to his fearlessness when hunting and fighting, he is suggested to be a debonair, polite gentleman given to moments of [[:wikt:gallantry|gallantry]], with a scholarly penchant for knowledge, a tendency to be pedantically accurate about details in his stories, and a deep appreciation for food and drink of all kinds.{{sfn|George|1918|pp=181–182}} The Baron also provides a solid geographical and social context for his narratives, peppering them with topical allusions and satire about recent events; indeed, many of the references in Raspe's original text are to historical incidents in the real-life Münchhausen's military career.{{sfn|Blamires|2009|loc=§12–13}}
Because the feats the Baron describes are overtly implausible, they are easily recognizable as fiction,{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=492}} with a strong implication that the Baron is a liar.{{sfn|George|1918|pp=169–171}} Whether he expects his audience to believe him varies from version to version; in Raspe's original 1785 text, he simply narrates his stories without further comment, but in the later extended versions he is insistent that he is telling the truth.{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=485}} In any case, the Baron appears to believe every word of his own stories, no matter how internally inconsistent they become, and he usually appears tolerantly indifferent to any disbelief he encounters in others.{{sfn|George|1918|pp=177–178}}
{{Gallery |title=Illustrations for the stories |width=160 | height=170 | lines=4 |align=center |File:Baron07a.gif |alt1=Refer to caption |The Baron returns from the Moon: illustration, possibly by Raspe, for the second edition of the book |File:Fronta.gif |alt2=Refer to caption |The anonymous 1792 portrait of the Baron |File:Cruik4.gif |alt3=Refer to caption |The Baron rides a half-horse, illustrated by George Cruikshank |File:Hosemann Münchhausen 11.png |alt4=Refer to caption |The Baron picks up a carriage, illustrated by Theodor Hosemann |File:Gustave Doré - Baron von Münchhausen - 067.jpg |alt5=Refer to caption |The Baron retrieved from the whale, illustrated by Gustave Doré }}
Illustrators of the Baron stories have included [[Thomas Rowlandson]], [[Alfred Crowquill]], [[George Cruikshank]], [[Ernst Ludwig Riepenhausen]], [[Theodor Hosemann]], [[Adolf Schrödter]], [[Gustave Doré]], [[William Strang]],{{sfn|Seccombe|1895|pp=xxxv–xxxvi}} [[W. Heath Robinson]],{{sfn|Blamires|2009|loc=§29}} and [[Ronald Searle]].{{sfn|Raspe|1969}} The Finnish-American cartoonist [[Klaus Nordling]] featured the Baron in a weekly ''Baron Munchausen'' comic strip from 1935 to 1937,{{sfn|Holtz|2011}} and in 1962, Raspe's text was adapted for ''[[Classics Illustrated]]'' #146 (British series), with both interior and cover art by the British cartoonist [[Denis Gifford]].{{sfn|Jones|2011|p=352}}
In the first published illustrations, which may have been drawn by Raspe himself, the Baron appears slim and youthful.{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=500}} For the 1792 ''Sequel to the Adventures of Baron Munchausen'', an anonymous artist drew the Baron as a dignified but tired old soldier whose face is marred by injuries from his adventures; this illustration remained the standard portrait of the Baron for about seventy years, and its imagery was echoed in Cruikshank's depictions of the character. Doré, illustrating a [[Théophile Gautier, fils|Théophile Gautier ''fils'']] translation in 1862, retained the sharply beaked nose and twirled moustache from the 1792 portrait, but gave the Baron a healthier and more affable appearance; the Doré Baron became the definitive visual representation for the character.{{sfn|Kareem|2012|pp=500–503}}
The relationship between the real and fictional Barons is complex. On the one hand, the fictional Baron Munchausen can be easily distinguished from the historical figure Hieronymus von Münchhausen;{{sfn|Fisher|2006|p=257}} the character is so separate from his namesake that at least one critic, the writer [[W. L. George]], concluded that the namesake's identity was irrelevant to the general reader,{{sfn|George|1918|pp=179–180}} and [[Richard Asher]] named [[Munchausen syndrome]] using the anglicized spelling so that the disorder would reference the character rather than the real person.{{sfn|Fisher|2006|p=257}} On the other hand, Münchhausen remains strongly connected to the character he inspired, and is still nicknamed the ''Lügenbaron'' ("Baron of Lies") in German.{{sfn|Fisher|2006|p=252}} As the Munchausen researcher Bernhard Wiebel has said, "These two barons are the same and they are not the same."{{sfn|Wiebel|2011}}
==Critical and popular reception== [[File:Bodenwerder-Münchhausen-Denkmal.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Refer to caption|Statue of Munchausen in Bodenwerder]] Reviewing the first edition of Raspe's book in December 1785, a writer in ''[[The Critical Review]]'' commented appreciatively:{{sfn|Seccombe|1895|p=vi}}
{{quote|This is a satirical production calculated to throw ridicule on the bold assertions of some parliamentary declaimers. If rant may be best foiled at its own weapons, the author's design is not ill-founded; for the marvellous has never been carried to a more whimsical and ludicrous extent.{{sfn|Seccombe|1895|p=vi}}{{efn|At the time, "ludicrous" was not a negative term; rather, it suggested that humor in the book was sharply satirical.{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=491}}}}}}
A writer for ''[[The English Review]]'' around the same time was less approving: "We do not understand how a collection of lies can be called a satire on lying, any more than the adventures of a woman of pleasure can be called a satire on fornication."{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=496}}
W. L. George described the fictional Baron as a "comic giant" of literature, describing his boasts as "splendid, purposeless lie[s] born of the joy of life".{{sfn|George|1918|p=169}} Théophile Gautier ''fils'' highlighted that the Baron's adventures are endowed with an "absurd logic pushed to the extreme and which backs away from nothing".{{sfn|Lefebvre|2011|p=60}} According to an interview, [[Jules Verne]] relished reading the Baron stories as a child, and used them as inspiration for his own adventure novels.{{sfn|Compère|Margot|Malbrancq|1998|p=232}} [[Thomas Seccombe]] commented that "Munchausen has undoubtedly achieved [a permanent place in literature]&nbsp;... The Baron's notoriety is universal, his character proverbial, and his name as familiar as that of Mr. [[Lemuel Gulliver]], or [[Robinson Crusoe]]."{{sfn|Seccombe|1895|p=v}}
[[Steven T. Byington]] wrote that "Munchausen's modest seat in the [[Valhalla]] of classic literature is undisputed", comparing the stories to American [[tall tale]]s and concluding that the Baron is "the patriarch, the perfect model, the fadeless fragrant flower, of liberty from accuracy".{{sfn|Byington|1928|pp=v–vi}} The folklore writer [[Alvin Schwartz (children's author)|Alvin Schwartz]] cited the Baron stories as one of the most important influences on the American tall tale tradition.{{sfn|Schwartz|1990|p=105}} In a 2012 study of the Baron, the literary scholar Sarah Tindal Kareem noted that "Munchausen embodies, in his deadpan presentation of absurdities, the novelty of fictionality [and] the sophistication of aesthetic illusion", adding that the additions to Raspe's text made by Kearsley and others tend to mask these ironic literary qualities by emphasizing that the Baron is lying.{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=485}}
By the beginning of the 19th century, Kearsley's phenomenally popular version of Raspe's book had spread to abridged [[chapbook]] editions for young readers, who soon became the main audience for the stories.{{sfn|Blamires|2009|loc=§24}} The book, especially in its adaptations for children, remained widely popular throughout the century.{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=503}} It was translated into nearly all languages spoken in Europe;{{sfn|Carswell|1952b|p=xxxiii}} [[Robert Southey]] referred to it as "a book which everybody knows, because all boys read it".{{sfn|Blamires|2009|loc=§24}} Notable later translations include Gautier's French rendering{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=500}} and [[Korney Chukovsky]]'s popular Russian adaptation.{{sfn|Balina|Goscilo|Lipovet︠s︡kiĭ|2005|p=247}} By the 1850s, ''Munchausen'' had come into [[slang]] use as a verb meaning "to tell extravagantly untruthful pseudo-autobiographical stories".{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=504}} [[Robert Chambers (publisher born 1802)|Robert Chambers]], in an 1863 almanac, cited the iconic 1792 illustration of the Baron by asking rhetorically:
{{quote|Who is there that has not, in his youth, enjoyed ''The Surprising Travels and Adventures of Baron Munchausen in Russia, the Caspian Sea, Iceland, Turkey, &c.'' a slim volume—all too short, indeed—illustrated by a formidable portrait of the baron in front, with his broad-sword laid over his shoulder, and several deep gashes on his manly countenance? I presume they must be few.{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=503}}}}
Though Raspe's book is no longer widely read by English speakers,{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=486}} the Munchausen stories remain popular in Europe, especially in Germany and in Russia.{{sfn|Baister|Patrick|2007|p=159}}
==In culture== ===Literature=== As well as the many augmented and adapted editions of Raspe's text, the fictional Baron has occasionally appeared in other standalone works.{{sfn|Blamires|2009|loc=§30}} In 1838–39, [[Karl Leberecht Immermann]] published the long novel ''Münchhausen: Eine Geschichte in Arabesken'' (''Münchhausen: A History of Arabesques''){{sfn|Ziolkowski|2007|p=78}} as an homage to the character, and [[Adolf Ellissen]]'s ''Munchausens Lügenabenteur'', an elaborate expansion of the stories, appeared in 1846.{{sfn|Carswell|1952b|p=xxxiii}} In his 1886 philosophical treatise ''[[Beyond Good and Evil]]'', [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] uses one of the Baron's adventures, the one in which he rescues himself from a swamp, as a metaphor for belief in complete metaphysical [[free will]]; Nietzsche calls this belief an attempt "to pull oneself up into existence by the hair, out of the swamps of nothingness".{{sfn|Nietzsche|2000|p=218}}
In the late 19th century, the Baron appeared as a character in [[John Kendrick Bangs]]'s comic novels ''[[A House-Boat on the Styx]]'', ''[[Pursuit of the House-Boat]]'', and ''[[The Enchanted Type-Writer]]''.{{Sfnm|Bangs|1895|1p=27|Bangs|1897|2p=27|Bangs|1899|3p=34}} Shortly after, in 1901, Bangs published ''[[Mr. Munchausen]]'', a collection of new Munchausen stories, closely following the style and humor of the original tales.{{sfn|Blamires|2009|loc=§30}} [[Hugo Gernsback]]'s second novel, ''Baron Münchhausen's New Scientific Adventures'', put the Baron character in a [[science fiction]] setting; the novel was serialized in ''[[The Electrical Experimenter]]'' from May 1915 to February 1917.{{sfn|Westfahl|2007|p=209}}
[[Pierre Henri Cami]]'s character Baron de Crac, a French soldier and courtier under [[Louis XV of France|Louis XV]],{{sfn|Cami|1926}} is an imitation of the Baron Munchausen stories.{{sfn|George|1918|p=175}} In 1998,{{sfn|Wardrip-Fruin|2009|p=77}} the British game designer [[James Wallis (games designer)|James Wallis]] used the Baron character to create a multi-player [[storytelling game]], ''[[The Extraordinary Adventures of Baron Munchausen]]'', in which players improvise Munchausen-like first-person stories while overcoming objections and other interruptions from opponents.{{sfn|Mitchell|McGee|2009|pp=100–102}}
===Stage and audio=== [[File:Cliff Hall and Jack Pearl 1952.JPG|thumb|upright|alt=Photograph of Jack Pearl and Cliff Hall|For radio, [[Jack Pearl]] (right) and Cliff Hall (left) played the Baron and his disbelieving foil Charlie, respectively.]] On stage, ''Harlequin Munchausen, or the Fountain of Love'', a [[pantomime]] based on the Raspe text, was produced in London in 1818,{{sfn|Kareem|2012|p=504}} and [[Herbert Eulenberg]] made the Baron the main character of a 1900 play, ''Münchhausen''.{{sfn|Eulenberg|1900}} The [[Expressionist]] writer [[Walter Hasenclever]] turned the stories into a comedy, ''Münchhausen'',{{sfn|Ziolkowski|2007|p=78}} in 1934.{{sfn|Furness|Humble|1991|p=114}} [[Grigori Gorin]] used the Baron as the hero of his 1976 play ''That Very Munchausen'';{{sfn|Balina|Goscilo|Lipovet︠s︡kiĭ|2005|pp=246–247}} a [[That Very Munchausen|film version]] was made in 1980.{{sfn|Hutchings|2004|pp=130–131}} ''Baron Prášil'', a Czech musical about the Baron, opened in 2010 in [[Prague, Czech Republic|Prague]].{{sfn|Košatka|2010}}{{efn|name=Prasil}} The following year, the National Black Light Theatre of Prague toured the United Kingdom with a nonmusical production of ''The Adventures of Baron Munchausen''.{{sfn|Czech Centre London|2011}}
In 1932, the comedy writer Billy Wells adapted Baron Munchausen for a [[radio comedy]] routine starring the comedians [[Jack Pearl]] and Cliff Hall.{{sfn|Erickson|2014|p=50}} In the routine, Pearl's Baron would relate his unbelievable experiences in a thick German accent to Hall's [[Straight man (stock character)|"straight man" character]], Charlie. When Charlie had had enough and expressed disbelief, the Baron would invariably retort: "Vass ''you'' dere, Sharlie?"{{sfn|Erickson|2014|p=51}} The line became a popular and much-quoted [[catchphrase]], and by early 1933 ''The Jack Pearl Show'' was the second most popular series on American radio (after [[Eddie Cantor]]'s program).{{sfn|Erickson|2014|p=51}} Pearl attempted to adapt his portrayal to film in ''[[Meet the Baron]]'' in 1933, playing a modern character mistaken for the Baron,{{sfn|Erickson|2014|p=51}} but the film was not a success.{{sfn|Erickson|2014|p=50}} Pearl's popularity gradually declined between 1933 and 1937, though he attempted to revive the Baron character several times before ending his last radio series in 1951.{{sfn|Erickson|2014|p=52}}
For a 1972 [[Caedmon Records]] recording of some of the stories, [[Peter Ustinov]] voiced the Baron. A review in ''[[The Reading Teacher]]'' noted that Ustinov's portrayal highlighted "the braggadocio personality of the Baron", with "self-adulation&nbsp;... plainly discernible in the intonational innuendo".{{sfn|Knight|1973|p=119}}
===Film=== [[File:Gottfried Franz - Munchhausen Underwater.jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=Refer to caption|The Baron travels underwater, illustrated by Gottfried Franz.]] The early French filmmaker [[Georges Méliès]], who greatly admired the Baron Munchausen stories,{{sfn|Lefebvre|2011|p=60}} filmed ''[[Baron Munchausen's Dream]]'' in 1911. Méliès's short silent film, which has little in common with the Raspe text, follows a sleeping Baron through a surrealistic succession of intoxication-induced dreams.{{sfn|Zipes|2010|p=43}} Méliès may also have used the Baron's journey to the moon as an inspiration for his well-known 1902 film ''[[A Trip to the Moon]]''.{{sfn|Lefebvre|2011|p=60}} In the late 1930s, he planned to collaborate with the [[Dada]] artist [[Hans Richter (artist)|Hans Richter]] on a new film version of the Baron stories, but the project was left unfinished at his death in 1938.{{sfn|Ezra|2000|p=20}} Richter attempted to complete it the following year, taking on [[Jacques Prévert]], [[Jacques Brunius]], and [[Maurice Henry]] as screenwriters, but the beginning of the [[Second World War]] put a permanent halt to the production.{{sfn|Sadoul|Morris|1972|p=25}}
The French animator [[Émile Cohl]] produced a version of the stories using [[silhouette]] [[cutout animation]] in 1913; other animated versions were produced by Richard Felgenauer in Germany in 1920, and by Paul Peroff in the United States in 1929.{{sfn|Sadoul|Morris|1972|p=25}} [[Colonel Heeza Liar]], the protagonist of the first animated cartoon series in cinema history, was created by [[John Randolph Bray]] in 1913 as an amalgamation of the Baron and [[Teddy Roosevelt]].{{sfn|Shull|Wilt|2004|p=17}} The Italian director [[Paolo Azzurri]] filmed ''The Adventures of Baron Munchausen'' in 1914,{{sfn|Zipes|2010|p=408}} and the British director [[F. Martin Thornton]] made a short silent film featuring the Baron, ''The New Adventures of Baron Munchausen'', the following year.{{sfn|Young|1997|p=441}} In 1940, the Czech director [[Martin Frič]] filmed ''[[Baron Prášil (film)|Baron Prášil]]'', starring the comic actor [[Vlasta Burian]] as a 20th-century descendant of the Baron.{{sfn|Česká televize}}{{efn|name=Prasil|Among Czech speakers, the fictional Baron is usually called Baron Prášil.{{sfn|Sadoul|Morris|1972|p=25}}}}
For the German film studio [[Universum Film AG|Ufa]]'s 25th anniversary in 1943, [[Joseph Goebbels]] hired the filmmaker [[Josef von Báky]] to direct ''[[Münchhausen (film)|Münchhausen]]'', a big-budget color film about the Baron.{{sfn|Hull|1969|pp=252–253}} David Stewart Hull describes [[Hans Albers]]'s Baron as "jovial but somewhat sinister",{{sfn|Hull|1969|p=254}} while Tobias Nagle writes that Albers imparts "a male and muscular zest for action and testosterone-driven adventure".{{sfn|Nagle|2010|p=269}} A German musical comedy, ''[[Münchhausen in Afrika]]'', made as a vehicle for the Austrian singing star [[Peter Alexander (Austrian performer)|Peter Alexander]], appeared in 1957.{{sfn|Arndt|von Brisinski|2006|p=103}} [[Karel Zeman]]'s 1961 Czech film ''[[The Fabulous Baron Munchausen]]'' commented on the Baron's adventures from a contemporary perspective, highlighting the importance of the poetic imagination to scientific achievement; Zeman's stylized ''[[mise-en-scène]]'', based on Doré's illustrations for the book, combined animation with live-action actors, including [[Miloš Kopecký]] as the Baron.{{sfn|Hames|2009|pp=197–198}}
In the [[Cinema of the Soviet Union|Soviet Union]], [[Soyuzmultfilm]] released a 16-minute [[stop-motion animation]] ''Adventures of Baron Munchausen'' in 1967, directed by Anatoly Karanovich.{{sfn|Venger & Reisner|loc=[http://www.animator.ru/db/?ver=eng&p=show_film&fid=2226 "Adventures of Baron Munghausen"] {{sic}}}} Another Soviet animated version was produced as a series of short films, ''[[Munchausen's Adventures]]'', in 1973 and 1974.{{sfn|Venger & Reisner|loc=[http://www.animator.ru/db/?ver=eng&p=show_film&fid=6754 "Munchausen's Adventures"]}} The French animator [[Jean Image]] filmed ''[[The Fabulous Adventures of the Legendary Baron Munchausen]]'' in 1979,{{sfn|Zipes|2010|p=408}} and followed it with a 1984 sequel, ''[[Moon Madness (film)|Moon Madness]]''.{{sfn|Willis|1984|p=184}} [[Oleg Yankovsky]] appeared as the Baron in the 1980 Russian television film ''[[That Same Munchausen]]'', directed by [[Mark Zakharov]] from Grigori Gorin's play. The film, a commentary on Soviet censorship and social mores, imagines an ostracized Baron attempting to prove the truth of his adventures in a disbelieving and [[conformity]]-driven world.{{sfn|Hutchings|2004|pp=130–131}}
In 1988, [[Terry Gilliam]] adapted the Raspe stories into a lavish Hollywood film, ''[[The Adventures of Baron Munchausen]]'', with the Canadian stage actor [[John Neville (actor)|John Neville]] in the lead. [[Roger Ebert]], in his review of the film, described Neville's Baron as a man who "seems sensible and matter-of-fact, as anyone would if they had spent a lifetime growing accustomed to the incredible".{{sfn|Ebert|1989}} The German actor [[Jan Josef Liefers]] starred in a 2012 two-part [[television film]] titled ''[[Baron Münchhausen (2012 film)|Baron Münchhausen]]''; according to a ''[[Spiegel Online]]'' review, his characterization of the Baron strongly resembled [[Johnny Depp]]'s performance as [[Jack Sparrow]] in the ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean (film series)|Pirates of the Caribbean]]'' film series.{{sfn|Hass|2012}}
==Legacy== ===Memorials=== [[File:Muenchhausen-1lats.jpg|thumb|alt=Refer to caption|Latvian commemorative coin of 2005]] In 2004, a fan club calling itself Munchausen's Grandchildren<!-- (Внучата Мюнхаузена) --> was founded in the Russian city of [[Kaliningrad]] (formerly [[Königsberg]]). The club's early activities included identifying "historical proofs" of the fictional Baron's travels through Königsberg, such as a [[jackboot]] supposedly belonging to the Baron{{sfn|Викторова|2004}} and a [[sperm whale]] skeleton said to be that of the whale in whose belly the Baron was trapped.{{sfn|Волошина|Захаров|2006}}
On 18 June 2005, to celebrate the 750th anniversary of Kaliningrad, a monument to the Baron was unveiled as a gift from Bodenwerder, portraying the Baron's cannonball ride.{{sfn|Kaliningrad-Aktuell|2005}} Bodenwerder sports a Munchausen monument in front of its Town Hall,{{sfn|Baister|Patrick|2007|p=159}} as well a Munchausen museum including a large collection of illustrated editions of the stories.{{sfn|Blamires|2009|loc=§32}} Another Munchausen Museum (''Minhauzena Muzejs'') exists in Duntes Muiža, [[Latvia]], home of the real Baron's first wife;{{sfn|Baister|Patrick|2007|p=154}} the couple had lived in the town for six years, before moving back to the baronial estate in Hanover.{{sfn|Baister|Patrick|2007|p=159}} In 2005, to mark the real-life Baron's 285th birthday, the [[National Bank of Latvia]] issued a commemorative silver coin.{{sfn|Baister|Patrick|2007|p=159}}
===Nomenclature=== In 1951, the British physician [[Richard Asher]] published an article in ''[[The Lancet]]'' describing patients whose [[factitious disorder]]s led them to lie about their own states of health. Asher proposed to call the disorder "Munchausen's syndrome", commenting: "Like the famous Baron von Munchausen, the persons affected have always travelled widely; and their stories, like those attributed to him, are both dramatic and untruthful. Accordingly, the syndrome is respectfully dedicated to the baron, and named after him".{{sfn|Olry|2002|p=54}} The disease is now usually referred to as [[Munchausen syndrome]].{{sfn|Fisher|2006|p=250}} The name has spawned two other coinages: [[Munchausen syndrome by proxy]], in which illness is feigned by caretakers rather than patients,{{sfn|Olry|2002|p=54}} and [[Munchausen by Internet]], in which illness is feigned online.{{sfn|Feldman|2000}}
In 1968, [[Hans Albert]] coined the term "[[Münchhausen trilemma]]" to describe the philosophical problem inherent in having to derive conclusions from premises; those premises have to be derived from still other premises, and so on forever, leading to an [[infinite regress]] interruptible only by [[circular logic]] or [[dogmatism]]. The problem is named after the similarly paradoxical story in which the Baron saves himself from being drowned in a swamp by pulling on his own hair.{{sfn|Apel|2001|pp=39–40}} The same story also inspired the mathematical term "[[Munchausen number]]", coined by Daan van Berkel in 2009 to describe numbers whose digits, when raised to their own powers, can be added together to form the number itself (for example, 3435&nbsp;=&nbsp;3<sup>3</sup>&nbsp;+&nbsp;4<sup>4</sup>&nbsp;+&nbsp;3<sup>3</sup>&nbsp;+&nbsp;5<sup>5</sup>).{{sfn|Orly|Haines|2013|p=136}}
Subclass ATU1889 of the [[Aarne–Thompson–Uther classification system]], a standard index of folklore, was named "Münchhausen Tales" in tribute to the stories.{{sfn|Ziolkowski|2007|p=77}} In 1994, a [[main belt asteroid]] was named [[14014 Münchhausen]] in honor of both the real and the fictional Baron.{{sfn|NASA|2013}}
